impactiii 2024-10-28 11:21 p.m.
PAPERLESS ORDER: The Court, having reviewed the allegations set forth in Count One of the charges against the Defendant under 1 M.S.C. § 2102 for Second Degree Murder, finds that the phrase "and wickedly" is irrelevant and constitutes inflammatory surplusage; therefore, it is strikeable as surplusage under Mayflower Rules of Criminal Procedure 3(2)(6). Accordingly, the Court strikes "and wickedly" from Count One, determining that its removal will not alter the substance of the offense charged. The State is ordered to produce their Superseding Information reflecting this Order by October 29, 2024, at 11:59 PM EST. Signed by Judge sadoimpacto on 10/28/2024.

MINUTE ORDER: It is ORDERED AND ADJUDGED that the Court confirms the State's obligation to disclose to the defendant all exculpatory evidence—namely, evidence that favors the defendant or casts doubt on the State's case—as required by the principles established in Brady v. Maryland, 373 U.S. 83 (1963) and its progeny. The State is hereby ORDERED to fulfill this obligation. The State has a duty to disclose any evidence that negates the defendant's guilt, affects the credibility of a witness, or could potentially reduce a sentence. The defendant is entitled to this information without needing to make a request. Failure to disclose exculpatory evidence in a timely manner may result in consequences, including, but not limited to, exclusion of evidence, dismissal of the information, contempt proceedings, disciplinary action, or sanctions by the Court. Signed by Judge sadoimpacto on 10/29/2024.

Jani 2024-11-02 09:20 p.m.
The phrase "All parties are ordered to adhere to the following pretrial timelines" means that everyone involved in a legal case, typically the plaintiff, defendant, and their legal representatives must follow a set schedule for completing specific tasks or submitting necessary documents before the trial begins. By adhering to these timelines, all parties ensure that the trial process is organized, fair, and efficient. Failure to meet these deadlines could result in disadvantages in the case.

California v. Trombetta is a reference for you Xolaaz.

U.S. v. Bakhtiar, 994 F.2d 970 (2d Cir. 1993):
Brady held that the prosecution violates a defendant's due process right to a fair trial if it withholds material exculpatory evidence, regardless of whether the prosecution acted in bad faith. Brady, at 87. Here, the prosecution lost the evidence, which presents a different problem. See Youngblood, 488 U.S. at 57; see also United States v. Bakhtiar, 994 F.2d 970, 975 (2d Cir. 1993)

The seminal authority here, Arizona v. Youngblood, 488 U.S. 51, 109 S.Ct. 333, 102 L.Ed.2d 281 (1988), suggests that defendants can be deprived of a fair trial only if the government acted in bad faith when evidence was lost or destroyed. But I am hesitant to apply Youngblood's bad faith standard here because, as noted in United States v. Bakhtiar, 994 F.2d 970, 975 (2d Cir. 1993), "the evidence at issue in Youngblood was of a sort only 'potentially' exculpatory—it had never been tested for determination of its exculpatory or inculpatory value." In contrast, the evidence here was key—not merely potentially exculpatory but integral to the defendant's defense—and the State's mishandling led to its loss. I have no doubt that said evidence was material and that it would play a substantial role in this case.

On October 29th, I ordered the State to, among other things, "disclose to the defendant all exculpatory evidence. . . as required by the principles established in Brady v. Maryland, 373 U.S. 83 (1963) and its progeny." Minute Order (Oct. 29, 2024). Inherent in the principles established in Brady and its progeny is the obligation for the State to (1) disclose evidence at a time when it is most favorable to the defendant (at the onset of the case if possible), and (2) preserve all evidence that has the potential to be exculpatory. If the evidence was lost on-part of the State's negligence, then (1) it can't be disclosed in a timely manner, and (2) it wasn't preserved.

The State was well warned in my order that "[f]ailure to disclose exculpatory evidence in a timely manner may result in consequences, including, but not limited to, exclusion of evidence, dismissal of the information, contempt proceedings, disciplinary action, or sanctions by the Court." Minute Order (Oct. 29, 2024). As I already said, there is no way for the State to disclose said evidence right now because it is gone; likewise, it has not been preserved.

Sanctions for negligent loss of evidence are appropriate and well within my power (United States v. Bryant, 439 F.2d 642 (D.C.Cir. 1971)), and I am seriously open to imposing such sanctions unless I can hear some kind of convincing argument from the State. Walk me back from this ledge—persuade me, don't just argue.
